HB98 INTRODUCED
29
30 A BILL
31 TO BE ENTITLED
32 AN ACT
33
34 Relating to scholarships; to establish a program to
35 grant tuition money to dependents of law enforcement officers
36 for use in participating public or private institutions of
37 higher education in the State of Alabama; to provide
38 requirements for scholarship eligibility; to provide
39 scholarship conditions and terms; to provide for
40 administration of the program by the Alabama Commission on
41 Higher Education; to establish the Alabama Law Enforcement
42 Officers Family Scholarship Fund; and to establish a
43 distinctive blackout license plate to help fund the
44 scholarship program.
45 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
46 Section 1. Article 11, commencing with Section
47 36-21-220, is added to Chapter 21 of Title 36, Code of Alabama
48 1975, to read as follows:
49 Article 11.
50 §36-21-220
51 This article shall be known and cited as the Alabama
52 Law Enforcement Officers' Family Scholarship Program.
53 §36-21-221
54 As used in this article, the following terms have the
55 following meanings:
56 (1) ACADEMIC PERIOD. A semester or quarter.
Page 2

(1) ACADEMIC PERIOD. A semester or quarter.
HB98 INTRODUCED
57 (2) APPROVED POSTSECONDARY PROGRAM. Any for-credit or
58 non-credit workforce or career training program or course of
59 study at the undergraduate level directed toward a vocational
60 certification, an associate degree, or a baccalaureate degree
61 offered by a participating institution. The term includes an
62 academic major.
63 (3) COMMISSION. The Alabama Commission on Higher
64 Education, including the commission's Office of Student
65 Assistance.
66 (4) ELIGIBLE DEPENDENT. An individual who, on the date
67 of applying for the scholarship provided under this article,
68 is:
69 a. Not eligible for the police officer's survivors
70 educational assistance provided under Article 5 of this
71 chapter; and
72 b. Either of the following:
73 1. A natural or adopted child of a qualifying law
74 enforcement officer, who is under 27 years of age, and who has
75 resided in the state for at least the two preceding years; or
76 2. The current or surviving spouse of a qualifying law
77 enforcement officer who has resided in the state for at least
78 the two preceding years.
79 (5) LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY. Any law enforcement
80 department or agency that serves the state, a municipality, a
81 county, or a postsecondary educational institution.
82 (6) PARTICIPATING INSTITUTION. An accredited public or
83 private postsecondary vocational school, technical school,
84 community or junior college, college, or university that
Page 3

community or junior college, college, or university that
HB98 INTRODUCED
85 enters into a contract with the board to accept reimbursement
86 for a scholarship awarded to an eligible dependent.
87 (7) QUALIFYING LAW ENFORCEMENT OFFICER. An individual
88 who:
89 a. Is or has been certified by the Alabama Peace
90 Officers' Standards and Training Commission.
91 b. Is employed full-time for at least seven years by a
92 single law enforcement agency in the state, or at least 12
93 continuous years on a full-time basis by more than one law
94 enforcement agency in the state.
95 c. If no longer employed in law enforcement or retired,
96 was not terminated from the most recent employment as a law
97 enforcement officer pursuant to a disciplinary action.
98 (8) REQUIRED EDUCATIONAL EXPENSES. Costs charged for
99 tuition, mandatory fees, and books or electronic and digital
100 media required on a course syllabus.
101 §36-21-222
102 (a) The Alabama Law Enforcement Officers' Family
103 Scholarship is established to reimburse participating
104 institutions on behalf of eligible dependents the cost of
105 required educational expenses for up to eight semesters or 16
106 quarters in an approved postsecondary program.
107 (b)(1) The scholarship shall pay required educational
108 expenses after any other amounts from public or private
109 scholarships, grants, aid, or gifts awarded by third parties
110 to the eligible dependent for the academic period have been
111 applied.
112 (2) The amount for each recipient shall be capped at
Page 4

(2) The amount for each recipient shall be capped at
HB98 INTRODUCED
113 three thousand dollars ($3,000) for each academic period.
114 (c) The scholarship may be granted to as many
115 dependents of one qualifying law enforcement officer as are
116 eligible and who comply with the requirements of this article.
117 (d) The scholarship shall be administered by the
118 commission.
119 (e)(1) Availability of the scholarship to eligible
120 dependents is subject to an annual appropriation to the
121 Alabama Law Enforcement Officers' Family Scholarship Program
122 in the annual Education Trust Fund Appropriation Act, which
123 shall not exceed ten million dollars ($10,000,000).
124 (2) Available money for the scholarship may be
125 supplemented by private donations.
126 (3) Reimbursement shall be made at the end of each
127 academic period by the commission to a participating
128 institution by certified invoice submitted by the institution
129 that is substantiated by the name of each student receiving
130 the scholarship, with the amount claimed for each student.
131 (f) Participating institutions shall enter into a
132 contract with the commission and agree to provide any records
133 to the commission upon request.
134 §36-21-223
135 The scholarship application by an eligible dependent
136 shall be submitted to the commission and include, but not be
137 limited to, the following:
138 (1) Documentation from the participating institution
139 that the applicant has been accepted for admission and is
140 enrolled as a student.
